 <exercise xml:id="intro-systems-exam">
  <!-- <title>Rewriting a Higher-Order ODE as a First-Order System</title> -->

  <statement>
    <p>
      Consider the second-order differential equation
    </p>

    <me>
      y'' - 3y' + 2y = 0.
    </me>

    <p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          Introduce new variables to rewrite this equation as an equivalent
          first-order system in two variables.
        </li>

        <li>
          Express the resulting system using vector notation
          <m>\vec{x}' = A\vec{x}</m> for some matrix <m>A</m>.
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </statement>

  <hint>
    <p>
      Let <m>x_1 = y</m> and <m>x_2 = y'</m>.  
      Then compute <m>x_1'</m> and <m>x_2'</m> using the original equation.
      Remember that <m>x_1' = y'</m> and that <m>y''</m> can be replaced with an
      expression involving <m>x_1</m> and <m>x_2</m>.
    </p>
  </hint>

  <answer>
    <p>
      One possible system is
      </p>
      <me>
      \begin{aligned}
      x_1' \amp= x_2, \\
      x_2' \amp= -2x_1 + 3x_2.
      \end{aligned}
      </me>

      <p>
      In vector form,
      </p>

      <me>
      \vec{x}' =
      \begin{bmatrix}
      0 \amp 1 \\
      -2 \amp 3
      \end{bmatrix}
      \vec{x}.
      </me>
  </answer>

  <solution>
    <p>
      (a)  
      We introduce the standard substitution for converting a second-order ODE
      into a first-order system:
    </p>

    <me>
      x_1 = y, \qquad x_2 = y'.
    </me>

    <p>
      Then
    </p>

    <me>
      x_1' = y' = x_2.
    </me>

    <p>
      To compute <m>x_2'</m>, use the original equation:
    </p>

    <me>
      y'' - 3y' + 2y = 0
      \quad\Rightarrow\quad
      y'' = 3y' - 2y.
    </me>

    <p>
      Substituting <m>x_1 = y</m> and <m>x_2 = y'</m> gives
    </p>

    <me>
      x_2' = 3x_2 - 2x_1.
    </me>

    <p>
      Therefore the first-order system is
    </p>

    <me>
      \begin{aligned}
      x_1' \amp= x_2, \\
      x_2' \amp= -2x_1 + 3x_2.
      \end{aligned}
    </me>

    <p>
      (b)
      In vector–matrix notation, with
    </p>

    <me>
      \vec{x} =
      \begin{bmatrix}
      x_1 \\
      x_2
      \end{bmatrix},
    </me>

    <p>
      the system becomes
    </p>

    <me>
      \vec{x}' =
      \begin{bmatrix}
      0 \amp 1 \\
      -2 \amp 3
      \end{bmatrix}
      \vec{x}.
    </me>

    <p>
      This is the standard first-order vector representation of the original
      second-order equation.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="two-tank-mixing-system">
  <!-- <title>Setting Up a System for a Two-Tank Mixing Problem</title> -->

  <statement>
    <p>
      Two tanks are connected in such a way that fluid flows between them.
      Tank A contains 200 liters of brine, and Tank B contains 150 liters.
      At time <m>t=0</m>, Tank A contains 30 kg of salt and Tank B contains 5 kg.
    </p>

    <p>
      A pump moves well‑stirred brine from Tank A into Tank B at a rate of
      <m>5 \text{ L/min}</m>.  
      Another pump moves well‑stirred brine from Tank B back into Tank A at a rate of
      <m>3 \text{ L/min}</m>.  
      There are no other inflows or outflows, so volumes remain constant.
    </p>

    <p>
      Let <m>x(t)</m> be the amount of salt (in kg) in Tank A at time <m>t</m>,
      and let <m>y(t)</m> be the amount of salt in Tank B at time <m>t</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Task:</strong>  
      Derive a system of differential equations for <m>x(t)</m> and <m>y(t)</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
    <figure xml:id="two-tank-diagram">
      <caption>
        Two interconnected mixing tanks with flow rates.
      </caption>

      <image width="80%">
       <description>
        Diagram showing two tanks, Tank A on the left and Tank B on the right
        with arrows indicating 5 liters per minute from A to B and
        3 liters per minute from B to A.
      </description>
        <latex-image>
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.0]

% Tank A
\draw[thick] (0,0) rectangle (3,2);
\node at (1.5,2.3) {Tank A};
\node at (1.5,1) {200 L};

% Tank B
\draw[thick] (6,0) rectangle (9,2);
\node at (7.5,2.3) {Tank B};
\node at (7.5,1) {150 L};

% Arrow A -> B (5 L/min)
\draw[->, thick] (3,1.5) -- (6,1.5);
\node at (4.5,1.8) {5 L/min};

% Arrow B -> A (3 L/min)
\draw[->, thick] (6,0.5) -- (3,0.5);
\node at (4.5,0.2) {3 L/min};

\end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
    </figure>
</p>

  </statement>

  <hint>
    <p>
      Use the standard “rate in minus rate out” principle.
      The concentration in each tank is “amount of salt divided by volume.”
      For example, the concentration in Tank A is <m>x(t)/200</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Multiply each concentration by its respective flow rate to obtain
      salt transport rates.
    </p>
  </hint>

  <answer>
    <p>
      The system is
    </p>

    <me>
      \begin{aligned}
      x' \amp= \frac{3}{150}y - \frac{5}{200}x, \\
      y' \amp= \frac{5}{200}x - \frac{3}{150}y.
      \end{aligned}
    </me>
  </answer>

  <solution>
    <p>
      The concentration in Tank A is <m>x/200</m> (kg/L),
      and Tank B has concentration <m>y/150</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Tank A:</strong>  
      Salt flows <em>in</em> from Tank B at rate
    </p>

    <me>
      (\text{flow rate from B to A}) \cdot (\text{concentration in B})
      = 3 \cdot \frac{y}{150}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Salt flows <em>out</em> to Tank B at rate
    </p>

    <me>
      5 \cdot \frac{x}{200}.
    </me>

    <p>
      So
    </p>

    <me>
      x' = 3\frac{y}{150} - 5\frac{x}{200}.
    </me>

    <p>
      <strong>Tank B:</strong>  
      Salt flows <em>in</em> from Tank A at
    </p>

    <me>
      5 \cdot \frac{x}{200},
    </me>

    <p>
      and flows <em>out</em> to Tank A at
    </p>

    <me>
      3 \cdot \frac{y}{150}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Therefore
    </p>

    <me>
      y' = 5\frac{x}{200} - 3\frac{y}{150}.
    </me>

    <p>
      This yields the system:
    </p>

    <me>
      \begin{aligned}
      x' \amp= \frac{3}{150}y - \frac{5}{200}x, \\
      y' \amp= \frac{5}{200}x - \frac{3}{150}y,
      \end{aligned}
    </me>

    <p>
      which correctly models the exchange of salt between the two tanks.
    </p>
  </solution>

</exercise>



  </exercises>

</section>
</handout>